{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17540016","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17540016"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:49:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:49:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16728"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16728","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16728"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.08,0.03,0.13,0.57]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9419"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101635"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9419","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9419"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16728"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84076"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"1315"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"11114"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22282"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34397"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35465"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35466"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43647"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101635","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101635"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the gynaecology clinic requesting contraception. She has regular menstrual cycles and is currently using condoms. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She has never been pregnant. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. A pelvic examination is normal and CST is obtained. She is interested in insertion of either a levonorgestrel or copper intrauterine device for long term contraception.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the advice that should be given regarding the copper and levonorgestrel intrauterine devices?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Both types of intrauterine device require seven days of additional contraception","Insertion of either device should be delayed until the start of next menstrual cycle","Neither type of intrauterine device provides protection until the next menstrual cycle","The levonorgestrel intrauterine device provides immediate contraceptive protection","The copper intrauterine device provides immediate contraceptive protection"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the timing of contraceptive effectiveness for different intrauterine devices is crucial for providing appropriate advice to patients. The copper and hormonal intrauterine devices work through different mechanisms and therefore have different onset times for contraceptive effectiveness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe copper intrauterine device provides immediate contraceptive protection\u003C/strong\u003E regardless of when in the menstrual cycle it is inserted. This is because copper ions create a sterile inflammatory reaction that is toxic to both sperm and eggs, and this effect begins immediately upon insertion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe levonorgestrel intrauterine device provides immediate contraceptive protection\u003C/strong\u003E only if inserted within the first seven days of the menstrual cycle. If inserted at any other time, additional contraceptive protection is required for seven days.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBoth types of intrauterine device require seven days of additional contraception\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. This only applies to the levonorgestrel device when inserted after day seven of the cycle; the copper device is effective immediately at any time.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInsertion of either device should be delayed until the start of next menstrual cycle\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. There is no need to delay insertion of either device until the next menstrual cycle. Both can be inserted at any time in the cycle, provided pregnancy is reasonably excluded. Timing of insertion may affect when contraceptive protection begins, but does not require waiting for the next cycle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeither type of intrauterine device provides protection until the next menstrual cycle\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as both devices can provide protection before the next cycle, with the copper device being effective immediately and the levonorgestrel device effective immediately if inserted within the first seven days of the cycle.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The copper intrauterine device provides immediate contraceptive protection upon insertion.","The copper intrauterine device is effective for up to 10 years and can be used as emergency contraception if inserted within 5 days of unprotected intercourse.","The levonorgestrel intrauterine device requires 7 days of additional contraceptive protection if inserted after day 7 of the menstrual cycle."],"references":["Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists (RANZCOG). Contraception: Clinical Guideline [Internet]. Melbourne: RANZCOG; 2023 [cited 2024 Dec 1]. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/Contraception-Clinical-Guideline.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84076"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16728"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84076","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84076"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-03T15:25:11+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-03T15:27:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9419"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101635"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"37","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/37"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf46","name":"Sexual Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76